-- "source": "# 2.1 \u2014 Stakeholder Identification & Analysis\n\n> *Who has a stake in this vehicle, what do they need, and how do those needs become engineering requirements?*\n\n```{note}\n\ud83d\udea7 **This notebook is a placeholder.** Content will be written here. The topics and guiding questions below define the intended scope.\n```\n\n## Topics Covered\n\n- Primary stakeholders: operators, pilots, passengers, mission commanders\n- Secondary stakeholders: maintainers, ground crews, ATC, regulators\n- Tertiary stakeholders: communities (noise), insurers, financiers, the public\n- Stakeholder mapping: power vs. interest matrices\n- Conflicting stakeholder interests and how they are resolved\n- The role of the customer vs. the role of the user (especially in military programs)\n\n## Guiding Questions\n\n1. Who defines 'success' for a given aerial vehicle program, and how might their definitions conflict?\n2. How does the stakeholder landscape differ between a commercial airliner, a military UAV, and a recreational drone?\n3. What mechanisms exist to resolve conflicts between a paying customer and a regulatory authority?\n4. Why are maintainers often the most neglected stakeholder in early design, and what are the consequences?\n"
-- }
