-- "source": "# 2.4 \u2014 Mission Profiles & Design Drivers\n\n> *Who has a stake in this vehicle, what do they need, and how do those needs become engineering requirements?*\n\n```{note}\n\ud83d\udea7 **This notebook is a placeholder.** Content will be written here. The topics and guiding questions below define the intended scope.\n```\n\n## Topics Covered\n\n- Mission segment definition: taxi, takeoff, climb, cruise, loiter, combat, descent, landing, reserve\n- Payload-range diagrams and their implications for structural design\n- Design mission vs. ferry mission vs. training mission\n- Military mission profiles: CAP, CAS, interdiction, ISR, SEAD\n- UAV missions: ISR, cargo delivery, swarm, autonomous combat\n- Identifying the most demanding segment: which segment sizes the aircraft?\n\n## Guiding Questions\n\n1. Why is the reserve fuel requirement often the single largest driver of aircraft size?\n2. How does a payload-range diagram physically represent design trade-offs?\n3. Why might a helicopter be sized by hover ceiling rather than cruise speed?\n4. How does an eVTOL's mission profile differ fundamentally from a traditional helicopter's?\n"
-- }
