-+  {
-+   "cell_type": "markdown",
-+   "id": "md-s02-05-a",
-+   "metadata": {},
-+   "source": [
-+    "# 2.5 — Design Drivers, Figures of Merit & Trade Studies\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "Requirements define what the aircraft must do. Design drivers are a smaller\n",
-+    "subset — the requirements that will actively control the design, in the sense that\n",
-+    "changing them would force a significant change to the aircraft's size, configuration,\n",
-+    "or cost structure. A 200 kg payload target for a small UAV is a design driver; a\n",
-+    "2 kg target for the nose badge is not.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "Distinguishing drivers from the full requirements set matters because early-stage\n",
-+    "design effort should concentrate on the drivers. If the team spends three weeks\n",
-+    "optimising a system that is not a driver, the aircraft does not improve. If it\n",
-+    "spends three weeks on the sizing constraint, the aircraft gets lighter, cheaper, or\n",
-+    "more capable.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "## Design Drivers Versus Design Constraints\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "A **design driver** is a requirement — or combination of requirements — that\n",
-+    "actively shapes the design, forcing specific choices about configuration, size, or\n",
-+    "technology. A **design constraint** is a requirement that must be satisfied but does\n",
-+    "not differentiate between competing designs because all plausible concepts meet it\n",
-+    "easily.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "For a 600 km range commercial transport, the field length requirement might be a\n",
-+    "driver: the combination of runway constraint and MTOW drives the high-lift system\n",
-+    "design, which in turn drives the structural weight of the wing trailing edge and the\n",
-+    "complexity of flap actuation. The requirement that cockpit instruments comply with\n",
-+    "FAR 25.1303 is a constraint — all modern aircraft meet it, so it does not\n",
-+    "differentiate between design concepts.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "Drivers change as the design matures. During conceptual sizing, the dominant drivers\n",
-+    "are usually range, payload, and field performance. During preliminary design,\n",
-+    "structural weight targets and systems integration requirements carry more weight.\n",
-+    "During detail design, manufacturing tolerances and component lifecycle targets may\n",
-+    "become drivers. The design team should re-examine the driver hierarchy at each major\n",
-+    "programme review and update it when the relative importance of requirements shifts\n",
-+    "{cite}`raymer2018`.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "## Figures of Merit\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "A figure of merit (FOM) is a scalar quantity that summarises some aspect of aircraft\n",
-+    "performance for comparison between competing designs or configurations. FOMs must be\n",
-+    "chosen carefully: using the wrong FOM leads to optimising for something that does not\n",
-+    "reflect operational value.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "Common figures of merit for commercial transport aircraft:\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "*Range-payload efficiency* — how much payload an aircraft carries how far per unit\n",
-+    "of fuel, measured in tonne-km per kg fuel or seat-km per litre. This is the\n",
-+    "commercial transport's primary economic metric {cite}`torenbeek2013`.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "*Seat-mile cost* — the total operating cost of flying one aircraft seat one mile. It\n",
-+    "is the unit cost metric used by airline fleet planners to compare aircraft across\n",
-+    "different size categories and technologies.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "*Dispatch reliability* — the fraction of scheduled departures that depart without\n",
-+    "technical delay. A figure commonly used by airline operations teams to evaluate fleet\n",
-+    "candidates; below 99% is generally considered unacceptable on high-frequency routes.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "*Payload fraction* — the ratio of payload weight to maximum takeoff weight. For\n",
-+    "commercial transports this typically ranges from 0.25 to 0.35; cargo aircraft may\n",
-+    "achieve higher values.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "For military aircraft, different figures of merit apply:\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "*Specific excess power* (Ps) — the rate of energy increase available at a given\n",
-+    "flight condition, in ft/s or m/s. Ps is the primary measure of fighter manoeuvre\n",
-+    "performance — a higher Ps means the aircraft can gain energy faster than an adversary\n",
-+    "{cite}`sadraey2012`.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "*Combat radius* — the distance the aircraft can fly to the target, complete the\n",
-+    "combat mission, and return without air-to-air refuelling.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "*Probability of survival per sortie* — a composite figure incorporating radar cross-\n",
-+    "section, infrared signature, electronic warfare capability, and speed, used to assess\n",
-+    "survivability in a threat environment.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "For UAVs, mission-specific figures dominate: area coverage rate (km² per hour) for\n",
-+    "ISR missions, delivery capacity per sortie for logistics missions, or sensor dwell\n",
-+    "time over the target for persistent surveillance.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "## Weighted Decision Matrices\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "When comparing multiple design concepts, weighted decision matrices provide a\n",
-+    "structured way to combine multiple figures of merit into a single comparison. Each\n",
-+    "concept is scored against each FOM criterion, the scores are multiplied by criterion\n",
-+    "weights and summed to produce a total {cite}`ullman2009`.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "The weights should reflect the relative importance of each criterion as determined by\n",
-+    "the stakeholder priority setting from Section 2.1. Scoring should be as objective as\n",
-+    "possible — where a quantitative FOM can be calculated, the score should track it.\n",
-+    "Where a criterion is more qualitative, a defined scoring scale with specific\n",
-+    "descriptions prevents individual assessors from applying it inconsistently.\n",
-+    "\n",
-+    "Figure 1 shows an example weighted decision matrix comparing four UAV concepts\n",
-+    "across five criteria. The total weighted score does not tell the team which concept\n",
-+    "to build — it shows where the trade space lies and which criteria control the\n",
-+    "comparison.\n"
-+   ]
-+  },
