-- "source": "# 5.1 \u2014 Configuration Options for Fixed-Wing Aircraft\n\n> *What does the vehicle look like, at the broadest level, and why?*\n\n```{note}\n\ud83d\udea7 **This notebook is a placeholder.** Content will be written here. The topics and guiding questions below define the intended scope.\n```\n\n## Topics Covered\n\n- Wing placement: high, mid, low wing \u2014 stability and structural implications\n- Wing planform: straight, tapered, swept, delta, BWB, box wing, joined wing\n- Tail configurations: conventional, T-tail, V-tail, H-tail, canard, tailless\n- Fuselage cross-section: circular, oval, double-bubble, blended\n- Engine placement: podded under-wing, rear fuselage, buried, over-wing\n- Canard vs. conventional: stability, trim drag, departure resistance\n\n## Guiding Questions\n\n1. Why do commercial transports almost universally use swept, low-wing, podded-engine configurations?\n2. What are the structural and aerodynamic penalties of a T-tail, and when is it worth accepting them?\n3. Why does a blended wing body offer potentially transformative efficiency but face serious certification challenges?\n4. When is a canard configuration aerodynamically advantageous, and what stability trade-offs does it introduce?\n"
-- }
